Texts such as the {{ill|Yamato-hime no Mikoto Seiki|ja|倭姫命世記|1=Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato-hime no Mikoto Seiki|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=}}, the {{ill|Amaterasu-za Ise Nisho Kōtaijingū Goshinza Jidai-ki|ja|天照坐伊勢二所皇太神宮御鎮座次第記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu-za Ise Nisho Kōtaijingū Goshinza Jidai-ki|qq=}}, and others identify "Seoritsu-hime" as another name for the deity enshrined at the {{ill|Aramatsuri-no-Miya|ja|荒祭宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aramatsuri-no-miya|qq=}}, a subsidiary shrine of [[:en:Ise Shrine|Ise Grand Shrine]]. It is hypothesized that the {{ill|Aramatsuri-no-Miya|ja|荒祭宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aramatsuri-no-miya|qq=}} once stood within the main sanctuary. According to Ise Shrine's official historical record, the two shrines at the time enshrined [[:en:Amaterasu|Amaterasu Ōmikami]] in the main shrine and her {{ill|Aramitama|ja|荒御魂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aramitama|qq=}} (wild spirit) in Aramatsuri-no-miya.<ref>[https://www.isejingu.or.jp/download/pdf/pamphlet_takihara.pdf Ise Shrine official pamphlet]</ref> If true, Seoritsu-hime, enshrined in the western part of the main shrine, could represent a distinct and revered deity.
== Associated Deities == Seoritsu-hime is closely associated with [[:en:Amaterasu|Amaterasu Ōmikami]], sometimes considered her {{ill|Aramitama|ja|荒御魂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aramitama|qq=}} (wild spirit). However, another interpretation identifies {{ill|Tsukisakakiitsu-no-mikoto|ja|撞賢木厳之御魂天疎向津媛命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukisakakiitsu-no-mikoto|qq=}} as a separate deity.<ref>[http://www.hirotahonsya.or.jp/yuisyopage/yuisyo_gosintoku.html Hirota Shrine official page]</ref>
